matic self</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F037074/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This project examines the development of post-genome science as a tool for improving population health.&amp;nbsp; It focuses on the science of nutrigenomics, which investigates interactions between genetic and nutritional variables that can lead to diet-related diseases such as type 2 diabetes and cardiovascular disease.&amp;nbsp; Nutrigenomics, it is suggested, allows dietary advice to be personalised to the individual?s unique genetic make-up, a service that is being made available commercially as direct-to-consumer genetic susceptibility testing.&amp;nbsp; Employing documentary sources and semi-structured interviews, the key characteristics of nutrigenomics that distinguish it from earlier genetic science (such as that underpinning the Human Genome Project) are identified, the use of this science to constitute and govern genetically at risk subjects is analysed, and the implications for roles and responsibilities in healthcare as this science becomes part of preventative medical practice are investigated.&amp;nbsp; The research examines how the notion of personal choice is central to nutrigenomic science, contemporary public health policy, and practices of preventative medicine.&amp;nbsp; Drawing conceptually on Foucauldian social theory, the operation of expertise within such an ethics of choice, in which the expert is a guide on our journey to healthy selfhood, is critically analysed. 
